<!--hvy: {"id":"overview","lock":false,"expanded":true,"highlight":false}-->
#! Overview

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  # Introduction
  
  Give your HVY document advanced functionality with scripting.
  
  The intended use for most people is to have AI write code for you instead of writing it yourself. Simply ask the AI to
  write it!
  
  The scripting plugin runs Python code (via Brython) once when the document loads. Use it to generate, mutate, or
  rearrange document content programmatically. Scripts do not have network access.
<!--hvy: {"id":"doc-api","lock":false,"expanded":true,"highlight":false}-->
#! The `doc` API

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  # The `doc` API

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  Your script runs with one global injected: `doc`. Everything you can do flows through it.
  
  - `doc.tool.TOOL_NAME(**args)` — call a supported synchronous document tool. Returns the tool's text result. Mutating
  tools update the document immediately. See [tools API](#tools-api) below
  - `doc.header.get(key)` / `doc.header.set(key, value)` / `doc.header.remove(key)` / `doc.header.keys()` — read and
  write the document's YAML front matter.
  - `doc.attachments.list()` — list attachment ids.
  - `doc.attachments.read(id)` — return the bytes of an attachment, or `None` if not present.
  - `doc.attachments.write(id, bytes, meta=None)` — create or replace an attachment.
  - `doc.attachments.remove(id)` — delete an attachment.
  - `doc.cli.run(command)` — run one synchronous virtual CLI command and return stdout. Use this for commands such as
  `hvy insert`, `hvy remove`, `hvy request_structure`, `cat`, `rg`, `find`, and `sed`. Use `doc.db` directly for SQL
  rather than `hvy plugin db-table query/exec`.
  - `doc.cli.write(path, content)` — replace a writable non-raw virtual file such as `/id/example/text.json` or
  `/id/example/text.txt` and return the write result.
  - `doc.json.parse(response)` / `doc.json.parse_array(response)` / `doc.json.parse_object(response)` — extract
  structured JSON from an LLM response, including fenced JSON or wrapper prose. Array/object helpers require that exact
  top-level shape and raise an error otherwise.
  - Plugin-provided APIs may also be present on `doc` when the relevant plugin is available. Use the relevant plugin's
  help for that API.
  - `doc.rerender()` — flush any pending re-render now (usually unnecessary; the host re-renders automatically when the
  script finishes).
  - `print(...)` — write a line to the script run log shown below the script in the editor. On failure, printed lines
  are shown above the traceback.
<!--hvy: {"id":"tools-api","lock":false,"expanded":true,"highlight":false}-->
#! Available tools

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  # Tools
  
  The scripting `doc.tool.TOOL_NAME(**args)` surface is a synchronous subset of the AI agent's document-edit tools. Pass
  tool arguments as Python keyword arguments; argument names match the AI tool schema.
  
  Document tools:
  
  - `request_structure` — get a structural summary.
  - `grep` — `query="...", flags="i"`.
  - `view_component` — `component_ref="C3"`.
  - `get_css` / `get_properties` / `set_properties`.
  - `patch_component` — `{ "component_ref": "C3", "edits": [...] }`.
  - `create_component` / `remove_component`.
  - `get_updated_components` — return changed and removed script component handles for local traversal/mutation after
  document updates. Removed handles have `removed = True`. On initial document load, this returns no components.
  - `get_components` — return all matching script component handles when a script explicitly needs a full scan.
  - `create_section` / `remove_section` / `reorder_section`.
  
   Component handle helpers returned by `get_components` and
   `get_updated_components`:
  
   - `handle.get(name)` / `handle.set(name, value)` — read or update `text` or a
   schema property.
   - `handle.has_tag(tag)` — test a component tag.
   - `handle.get_parent_by_tag(tag)` — find the nearest tagged ancestor
   component or section.
   - `handle.get_ancestor_record(excluded_tags="")` — find the nearest ancestor
   reusable record component.
   - `handle.first_table_cell(index=0)` — read the first cell at `index` from a
   nested table.
   - `handle.remove_children_by_tag(tag, slot="expandable-content")` — remove
   tagged child components from a child slot.
   - `handle.append_child(component, config=None, text="", slot="expandable-content")`
   — append a child component and return its handle.
  
  Header tools:
  
  - `view_header`, `grep_header`, `patch_header`.
  
  `edit_component`, `view_rendered_component`, `query_db_table`, `execute_sql`, and other async tools are not exposed
  through `doc.tool`.
<!--hvy: {"id":"execution-model","lock":false,"expanded":false,"highlight":false}-->
#! Execution model

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  Script source is wrapped in a generated function before Brython runs it, so
  `return` can stop the script early. Scripts receive a `doc` global and may
  define functions, local variables, loops, and conditionals like ordinary
  Python.
<!--hvy: {"id":"line-budget","lock":false,"expanded":false,"highlight":false}-->
#! Line budget

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  Every executed statement bumps a counter. By default the budget is
  100,000 lines. If your script exceeds it, execution stops with an error.
  Tight loops are bounded the same way as straight-line code: each pass
  through a loop body counts.
<!--hvy: {"id":"examples","lock":false,"expanded":false,"highlight":false}-->
#! Examples

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  Print the document's structural summary by writing it into the header:
  
  ```python
  summary = doc.tool.request_structure()
  doc.header.set("script_summary", summary[:200])
  ```
  
  Tag every section that mentions "TODO":
  
  ```python
  hits = doc.tool.grep(query="TODO", flags="i")
  doc.header.set("todo_hits", hits)
  ```
  
  Use the virtual CLI from a script:
  
  ```python
  out = doc.cli.run("hvy request_structure --collapse")
  doc.header.set("structure_preview", out[:200])
  ```
  
  Parse a structured LLM response inside an AI form submit script:
  
  ```python
  cards = doc.json.parse_array(response)
  first_question = str(cards[0].get("question", ""))
  doc.header.set("first_generated_question", first_question)
  ```
<!--hvy: {"id":"limits","lock":false,"expanded":false,"highlight":false}-->
#! Limits and security

 <!--hvy:text {}-->
  - No network: `fetch`, `XMLHttpRequest`, etc. are not exposed to scripts
    in this version.
  - No DOM: scripts cannot reach the rendered HTML; mutate the document
    through `doc` instead.
  - Errors abort the script and surface in the editor's status bar.
  - Scripts run synchronously on document load. Long scripts will block
    the first paint until they finish.
